\ncontent!: string;\n```\n\nAnd `IsMessageContent` validator:\n```typescript\nva
lidate(value: unknown, args: ValidationArguments) {\n  if (typeof value !== "str
ing") {\n    return false;\n  }\n  const type = (args.object as Record<string, u
nknown>).type;\n  if (type === "text" && value.length > 500) {\n    return false
;\n  }\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\nThis validator requires `content` to be a stri
ng for ALL message types, including image. But according to the review and PRD, 
image messages should be able to have empty/missing content (or the content coul
d be a URL).\n\nActually wait - looking at `im.service.ts` line 86:\n```typescri
pt\nif (dto.type === "image" && !dto.content) {\n  throw new BusinessException(\
n    1003,\n    "Image message requires a content URL",\n    HttpStatus.BAD_REQU
EST,\n  );\n}\n```\n\nThis suggests image messages DO require content (the URL).
But the review says:\n"问题: content 字段有 @IsString()（未加 @IsOptional()），
同时 @ValidateIf 仅作用于 @MaxLength。因此当 type = "image" 时，若 content 为空
或缺失，ValidationPipe 会在 Controller 层拦截请求，返回 400。"\n\nAnd the fix su
ggestion was:\n```typescript\n@IsOptional()\n@ValidateIf((o) => o.type === \'tex
t\')\n@IsString()\n@MaxLength(500)\ncontent?: string;\n```\n\nSo image messages 
should be allowed to not have content, and the service-level check would return 
400 if needed. But actually, the service DOES check for image content. So maybe 
the fix should be to make content optional in the DTO but keep the service valid
ation?\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the review and the service code - 
the service expects `content` for image messages to be the image URL. So maybe c
ontent IS required for images too. The issue might be that the original DTO had 
`@IsString()` and `@MaxLength(500)` where `@MaxLength` had a `@ValidateIf` but `
@IsString` didn\'t, meaning image messages with content would pass but image mes
sages without content would fail at DTO level.\n\nBut now with `@IsMessageConten
t()`, the validator always requires a string value. For MVP, maybe image message
s DO need a content URL. So this might not actually be a bug if we expect conten
t to always be present.\n\nHmm, but the review explicitly flagged this as a Majo
r issue. And looking at the service code, it does have validation for image cont
ent being missing - which implies the DTO should allow it through to the service
layer.\n\nLet me fix the DTO to make content optional, so the service can handle
the validation. This aligns with the review recommendation.\n\nWait, let me re-r
ead the validator more carefully:\n```typescript\nvalidate(value: unknown, args:
ValidationArguments) {\n  if (typeof value !== "string") {\n    return false;\n 
}\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nIf I make `content` optional in the DTO (`@IsOptional()`), t
hen when content is missing, the validator won\'t even be called because `@IsOpt
ional()` skips validation for undefined/null values. But then image messages wit
hout content would pass DTO validation and hit the service, where they would get
the 400 error.\n\nActually, looking at this again - the current validator `@IsMe
ssageContent()` was ADDED in the latest commit (as shown in the git diff). This 
was probably the fix for the review issue about `@MaxLength(500)` being applied 
conditionally. But the fix didn\'t go far enough - it still requires content to 
be present.\n\nLet me fix this properly by making content optional in the DTO an
d adjusting the validator to handle optional values.\n\nActually, let me think a
bout this more carefully. The validator was created as a custom validator. If I 
add `@IsOptional()` before `@IsMessageContent()`, then when content is null/unde
fined, the validation will be skipped entirely. Then the service-level check wil
l catch image messages without content.\n\nFor text messages, if content is miss
ing, `@IsOptional()` will skip validation, and the service doesn\'t have a speci
fic check for missing text content (it only checks `!dto.content || dto.content.
length > 500`). Wait, actually it does:\n```typescript\nif (dto.type === "text" 
&& (!dto.content || dto.content.length > 500)) {\n```\n\nSo missing text content
would be caught in the service too. Good.\n\nSo the fix is simple: add `@IsOptio
nal()` to `content` in `SendMessageDto`.\n\nBut wait, there\'s another issue. Th
e `IsMessageContent` validator reads `type` from `args.object`. But if `@IsOptio
nal()` causes validation to be skipped when content is missing, then the validat
or won\'t run. That\'s fine.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe the custom va
lidator itself should handle the optional case. If we add `@IsOptional()` and th
e validator only runs when content is present, that\'s fine.\n\nLet me also chec
k if there are any other remaining issues. Let me look at the `docs/design-docs/
flutter.md` and `nestjs.md` to see if there are any other violations.\n\nActuall
y, I should also check if the `MatchingModule` still imports `ImModule` anywhere
